{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17599590","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17599590"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:57:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:57:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15582"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15582"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.88,0,0.06,0.06,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8273"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70375"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8273"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15582"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55839"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"281"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5103"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19982"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19984"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70375"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with symptoms suggestive of thyroid dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following symptoms is most consistent with hypothyroidism rather than hyperthyroidism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cold intolerance","Weight loss","Palpitations","Heat intolerance","Tremor"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of the contrasting clinical features of thyroid dysfunction. \u003Cstrong\u003ECold intolerance\u003C/strong\u003E is a characteristic feature of hypothyroidism due to decreased metabolic rate and heat production. In contrast, \u003Cstrong\u003Eweight loss\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Epalpitations\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eheat intolerance\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Etremor\u003C/strong\u003E are all typical manifestations of hyperthyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn hyperthyroidism, excess thyroid hormone leads to increased metabolic rate, resulting in:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EIncreased heat production causing heat intolerance\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EIncreased cardiac contractility causing palpitations and tachycardia\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003EIncreased catabolism leading to weight loss despite normal or increased appetite\u003C/li\u003E    \u003Cli\u003ESympathetic overactivity causing tremor and anxiety\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypothyroidism presents with opposite features including cold intolerance, weight gain, bradycardia, and lethargy due to decreased metabolic rate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hyperthyroidism causes increased metabolic rate leading to heat intolerance, weight loss, and sympathetic overactivity","Hypothyroidism causes decreased metabolic rate leading to cold intolerance, weight gain, and bradycardia","The clinical features of thyroid dysfunction are largely opposite between hyper- and hypothyroid states"],"references":["De Leo S, Lee SY, Braverman LE. Hyperthyroidism. Lancet. 2016 Aug 27;388(10047):906-918. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(16)00278-6. Epub 2016 Mar 30. PMID: 27038492; PMCID: PMC5014602.","Doubleday AR, Sippel RS. Hyperthyroidism. Gland Surg. 2020 Feb;9(1):124-135. doi: 10.21037/gs.2019.11.01. PMID: 32206604; PMCID: PMC7082267.","Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55839"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15582"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55839"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-14T20:09:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-14T20:10:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8273"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70375"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"r